# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ship-motions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] An aircraft in flight is free to rotate in three dimensions: ***yaw***, nose left or right about an axis running up and down; ***pitch***, nose up or down about an axis running from wing to wing; and ***roll***, rotation about an axis running from nose to tail.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The yaw, pitch, and roll axes are alternatively designated as *vertical*, *lateral* (or *transverse*), and *longitudinal* respectively.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] These axes move with the vehicle and rotate relative to the Earth along with the craft.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] These definitions were analogously applied to spacecraft when the first crewed spacecraft were designed in the late 1950s.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] These rotations are produced by torques (or moments) about the principal axes.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] On an aircraft, these are intentionally produced by means of moving control surfaces, which vary the distribution of the net aerodynamic force about the vehicle's center of gravity.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Elevators (moving flaps on the horizontal tail) produce pitch, a rudder on the vertical tail produces yaw, and ailerons (flaps on the wings that move in opposing directions) produce roll.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] On a spacecraft, the movements are usually produced by a reaction control system consisting of small rocket thrusters used to apply asymmetrical thrust on the vehicle.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Normally, these axes are represented by the letters X, Y and Z in order to compare them with some reference frame, usually named x, y, z.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Normally, this is made in such a way that the X is used for the longitudinal axis, but there are other possibilities to do it.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The **yaw axis** has its origin at the center of gravity and is directed towards the bottom of the aircraft, perpendicular to the wings and to the fuselage reference line.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Motion about this axis is called **yaw**.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] A positive yawing motion moves the nose of the aircraft to the right.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The rudder is the primary control of yaw.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The term *yaw* was originally applied in sailing, and referred to the motion of an unsteady ship rotating about its vertical axis.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The **pitch axis** (also called **transverse** or **lateral axis**) passes through an aircraft from wingtip to wingtip.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Rotation about this axis is called **pitch**.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Pitch changes the vertical direction that the aircraft's nose is pointing (a positive pitching motion raises the nose of the aircraft up and lowers the tail).
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The elevators are the primary control surfaces for pitch.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The **roll axis** (or **longitudinal axis**) has its origin at the center of gravity and is directed forward, parallel to the fuselage reference line.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Motion about this axis is called **roll**.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] An angular displacement about this axis is called **bank**.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] A positive rolling motion lifts the left wing and lowers the right wing.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The pilot rolls by increasing the lift on one wing and decreasing it on the other.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The ailerons are the primary control of roll.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The rudder also has a secondary effect on roll.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] These axes are related to the principal axes of inertia, but are not the same.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] They are geometrical symmetry axes, regardless of the mass distribution of the aircraft.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] In aeronautical and aerospace engineering intrinsic rotations around these axes are often called Euler angles, but this conflicts with existing usage elsewhere.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The calculus behind them is similar to the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] Performing a rotation in an intrinsic reference frame is equivalent to right-multiplying its characteristic matrix (the matrix that has the vectors of the reference frame as columns) by the matrix of the rotation.
[src:ship-motions/aircraft-principal-axes] The first aircraft to demonstrate active control about all three axes was the Wright brothers' 1902 glider.
[src:ship-motions/angle-of-list] The **angle of list** is the degree to which a vessel heels (leans or tilts) to either port or starboard at equilibrium—with no external forces acting upon it.
[src:ship-motions/angle-of-list] If a listing ship goes beyond the point where a righting moment will keep it afloat, it will capsize and potentially sink.
[src:ship-motions/angle-of-list] Listing is caused by the off-centerline distribution of weight aboard due to uneven loading or to flooding.
[src:ship-motions/angle-of-list] By contrast, *roll* is the dynamic movement from side to side caused by waves.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] A single partially filled tank that extends across the full breadth of the vessel.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Its shape, size and internal baffles allow the liquid inside to slosh from side to side in response to the roll motion of the ship.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The phasing of the roll moments acting on the ship and the resultant liquid motion will be such that it reduces the roll motion.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] This type of tank was first investigated by William Froude, but did not receive much attention until the 1950s when it was revived and used in many naval vessels.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] They have the added advantage that it is possible to vary tank natural frequency by changes in water level and thus accommodate changes in a ship's metacentric height.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Free surface tanks are commonly referred to as "flume" tanks.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The use of these tanks was pioneered by Herr H.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Frahm in Germany at the start of the 20th century and they are often referred to as Frahm tanks.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] These partially filled tanks consist of two wing tanks connected at the bottom by a substantial crossover duct.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The air columns above the liquid in the two tanks are also connected by a duct.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] As in the free surface tanks, as the ship begins to roll the fluid flows from wing tank to wing tank causing a time varying roll moment to the ship and with careful design this roll moment is of correct phasing to reduce the roll motion of the ship.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] They do not restrict fore and aft passage as space above and below the water-crossover duct is available for other purposes.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] This was another concept introduced by Frahm and used in several ships in the early 1900s.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] In this concept the two wing tanks are connected only by an air duct at the top.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Water flows in and out of each tank via an opening in the hull to the sea.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] This eliminates the need for a crossover duct as in the other designs, but has its own set of disadvantages.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] This design promoted corrosion of the tanks due to the explicit interaction with sea water.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The holes on the hull cause resistance to forward motion.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The force required to accelerate sea water outside the ship (which is initially at rest) to the speed of the ship as it enters the ship is a substantial drag component (momentum drag) as its magnitude increases with the square of ship speed.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] More recently, a variation of these tanks has been used in oil drilling rig applications where forward motion is of little relevance.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] This is similar to a U-tube tank but the water crossover duct is much larger and the air crossover contains a servo-controlled valve system.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Since this valve controls the flow of air very little power is required.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] When the valve is closed, passage of air from one tank to the other is prevented and the resulting compression of air in the tank prevents flow of water also.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] When the valve opens, free movement of water and air is possible.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The border between controlled-passive and active stabilisation is not that distinct.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Active stabilisation generally implies that the system requires the use of machinery of significant power and the system must be much more effective in reducing roll in order to justify this high cost.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] This concept utilises an axial flow pump to force the water from one side of the ship to other rather than allowing it to slosh as in passive systems.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Webster (1967) studied the design of such a tank in detail.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The main disadvantage to this is that when the pump is operated there is a time lag for a sizeable amount of fluid to arrive at a tank, thus limiting instant roll stabilization.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Hence, compared to fin stabiliser systems, this is highly inefficient.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] Instead of consuming energy to control the flow inside the tank, this concept utilises a water turbine to produce electricity using the water that sloshes into the tank as in passive systems.
[src:ship-motions/antiroll-tanks] The main advantages to this are operating cost reduction by replacing part of fuel consumption and control of water flow without any mechanical mobile device.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In navigation, **bearing** or **azimuth** is the horizontal angle between the direction of an object and north or another object.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The angle value can be specified in various angular units, such as degrees, mils, or grad.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The bearing of the opposite direction (180° apart) is also known as a ***reciprocal bearing***; it forms a ***reciprocal line*** with the original bearing, e.g., the east-west line.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Historically, the US Army defined the *bearing* from point A to point B as the smallest angle between the ray AB and either north *or* south, whichever is closest.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] But this has fallen out of use since the 1940s.The bearing was expressed in terms of 2 characters and 1 number: first, the character is either N or S; next is the angle numerical value; third, the character representing the perpendicular direction, either E or W.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The bearing angle value will always be less than 90 degrees.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] For example, if Point B is located exactly southeast of Point A, the bearing from Point A to Point B is "S 45° E".
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] For example, if the bearing between Point A and Point B is S 45° E, the azimuth between Point A and Point B is 135°.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In nautical navigation the **absolute bearing** is the clockwise angle between north and an object observed from the vessel.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] If the north used as reference is the true geographical north then the bearing is a *true bearing* whereas if the reference used is magnetic north then the bearing is a *magnetic bearing*.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] An absolute bearing is measured with a bearing compass.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The measurement of absolute bearings of fixed landmarks and other navigation aids is useful for the navigator because this information can be used on the nautical chart together with simple geometrical techniques to aid in determining the position of the vessel.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] A *grid bearing* (also known as grid azimuth) is measured in relation to the fixed horizontal reference plane of grid north, that is, using the direction northwards along the grid lines of the map projection as a reference point.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] A *compass bearing*, as in vehicle or marine navigation, is measured in relation to the magnetic compass of the navigator's vehicle or vessel (if aboard ship).
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] It should be very close to the magnetic bearing.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In nautical navigation the **relative bearing** of an object is the clockwise angle from the heading of the vessel to a straight line drawn from the observation station on the vessel to the object.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The relative bearing is measured with a pelorus or other optical and electronic aids to navigation such as a periscope, sonar system, and radar systems.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Since World War II, relative bearings of such diverse point sources have been and are calibrated carefully to one another.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The United States Navy operates a special range off Puerto Rico and another on the west coast to perform such systems integration.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Relative bearings then serve as the baseline data for converting relative directional data into true bearings (N-S-E-W, relative to the Earth's true geography).
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] By contrast, Compass bearings have a varying error factor at differing locations about the globe, and are less reliable than the compensated or true bearings.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The measurement of relative bearings of fixed landmarks and other navigational aids is useful for the navigator because this information can be used on the nautical chart together with simple geometrical techniques to aid in determining the vessel's position, speed, course, etc.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The measurement of relative bearings of other vessels and objects in movement is useful to the navigator in avoiding the danger of collision.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] A bearing can be taken on another vessel to aid piloting.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] If the two vessels are travelling towards each other and the relative bearing remains the same over time, there is likelihood of collision and action needs to be taken by one or both vessels to prevent this from happening.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] A bearing can be taken to a fixed or moving object in order to target it with gunfire or missiles.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] This is mainly used by ground troops when planning on using an air-strike on the target.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] A bearing can be taken to a person or vessel in distress in order to go to their aid.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In aircraft navigation, an angle is normally measured from the aircraft's track or heading, in a clockwise direction.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] If the aircraft encounters a target that is not ahead of the aircraft and not on an identical track, then the angular bearing to that target is called a *relative bearing*.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In marine navigation, starboard bearings are 'green' and port bearings are 'red'.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Thus, in ship navigation, a target directly off the starboard side would be 'Green090' or 'G090'.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] This method is only used for a *relative bearing*.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] A navigator on watch does not always have a corrected compass available with which to give an accurate bearing.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] If available, the bearing might not be numerate.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Therefore, every forty-five degrees of direction from north on the compass was divided into four 'points'.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Thus, 32 points of 11.25° each makes a circle of 360°.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] An object at 022.5° relative would be 'two points off the starboard bow', an object at 101.25° relative would be 'one point abaft the starboard beam' and an object at 213.75° relative would be 'three points on the port quarter'.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] An informal method of measuring a *relative bearing* is by using the 'clock method'.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In this method, the direction a vessel, aircraft or object is measured as if a clock face is laid over the vessel or aircraft, with the number twelve pointing forward.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Something straight ahead is at 'twelve o'clock', while something directly off to the right is at 'three o'clock'.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] This method is only used for a relative bearing.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In land surveying, a **bearing** is the clockwise or counterclockwise angle between north or south and a direction.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] For example, bearings are recorded as N57°E, S51°E, S21°W, N87°W, or N15°W.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In surveying, bearings can be referenced to true north, magnetic north, grid north (the Y axis of a map projection), or a previous map, which is often a historical magnetic north.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] If navigating by gyrocompass, the reference direction is true north, in which case the terms *true bearing* and *geodetic bearing* are used.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In stellar navigation, the reference direction is that of the North Star, Polaris.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] In satellite broadcasting, a **bearing** is the combination of antenna azimuth and elevation required to point (aim) a satellite dish antenna in a given direction.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The bearing for geostationary satellites is constant.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] The bearing for polar-orbiting satellites varies continuously.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Moving from A to B along a great circle can be considered as always going in the same direction (the direction of B), such as when holding fixed a steering wheel or ship's wheel.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] However, following a great circle does *not* keep the same bearing, which applies when following a rhumb line.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Accordingly, the direction at A of B, expressed as a bearing, is not in general the opposite of the direction at B of A (when traveling on the great circle formed by A and B); see inverse geodetic problem.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] For example, assume A and B in the northern hemisphere have the same latitude, and at A the direction to B is east-northeast.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Then going from A to B, one arrives at B with the direction east-southeast, and conversely, the direction at B of A is west-northwest.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] To "keep to a bearing" is not, in general, the same as going in a fixed direction along a great circle.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Conversely, one can keep to a great circle and the bearing may change.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Thus the bearing of a straight path crossing the North Pole changes abruptly at the Pole from North to South.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] When travelling East or West, it is only on the Equator that one can keep East or West and be going straight (without the need to adjust).
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] Anywhere else, maintaining latitude requires a change in direction, requires adjustment.
[src:ship-motions/bearing-navigation] This change in direction becomes increasingly negligible as one moves to a lower latitude.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] A **bilge keel** is a nautical device used to reduce a ship's tendency to roll.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels are employed in pairs, one for each side of the ship.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] A ship may have more than one bilge keel per side, but this is rare.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels increase hydrodynamic resistance, making the ship roll less.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels are passive stability systems.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] On commercial shipping the bilge keel is in the form of a strake, or small keel or blister, running along much of the length of the hull.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] They are typically fitted one on each side, low down on the side of the hull, so as not to increase the draft of the vessel.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] In battleships they were often quite large and used as part of the torpedo protection system.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] A bilge keel is often in a "V" shape, welded along the length of the ship at the turn of the bilge.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Although not as effective as stabilizing fins, bilge keels have a major advantage in their low impact on internal ship arrangements.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Unlike fins, bilge keels do not have any components inside the hull that would adversely affect cargo or mission spaces.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Like fins, bilge keels have the disadvantage of increasing the hydrodynamic resistance of the vessel, thus hindering forward motion.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] When designing a bilge keel there are important decisions to consider.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] To minimize hydrodynamic drag the bilge keel should be placed in way of a flowline where it does not oppose crossflow.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] For such a usage the ends of the bilge keel should be tapered and properly faired into the hull.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Also, a bilge keel should not protrude from the hull so far that the device could be damaged when the vessel is alongside a pier, even with a few degrees of adverse heel.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels on commercial vessels should not protrude below the baseline either, where they could be damaged or fouled by grounding.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Note that small bilge keels are often fitted to smaller fishing boats precisely to protect the hull on drying moorings and to help keep the vessel upright.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] A bilge keel is constructed from flat plate so as to present a sharp obstruction to roll motion.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] The roll damping provided by a bilge keel is more than that of a barehull ship, but falls short of other roll damping devices.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Nevertheless, it is considered prudent naval architecture to install a bilge keel whenever possible as it is the only device effective in the severest of seas.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels can also be used in conjunction with other roll damping devices.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels are often fitted to smaller sailing yachts.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels minimise the draft of the vessel compared to a single fin keel thus enabling it to negotiate shallower water.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels on sailing yachts extend below the lowest point of the hull extending slightly outwards.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Such an arrangement also enables the vessel to stand upright on firm sand or mud at drying moorings without the need for detachable legs, and is simpler than retractable fin keels while giving the hull greater protection.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] Bilge keels are not as effective as central fin keels in preventing leeway (sideways slippage) caused by crosswinds but are preferred by many small craft owners due to their other advantages.
[src:ship-motions/bilge-keel] The first ship to be equipped with bilge keels was SS *Parisian*, which was launched in Scotland in 1880.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] The **bow** (/baʊ/) is the forward part of the hull of a ship or boat, the point that is farthest forward when the vessel is underway in the usual direction.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] A ship's bow should be designed to enable the hull to pass efficiently through the water.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] Bow shapes vary according to the speed of the boat, the seas or waterways being navigated, and the vessel's function.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] Where sea conditions are likely to promote pitching, it is useful if the bow provides reserve buoyancy; a flared bow (a raked stem with flared topsides) is ideal to reduce the amount of water shipped over the bow.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] Ideally, the bow's shape should both reduce water resistance and block water from regularly washing over the top of it.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] Large commercial barges on inland waterways rarely meet big waves and may have remarkably little freeboard at the bow, whereas fast military vessels operating offshore must be able to cope with heavy seas.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] On slower ships like tankers and barges, a fuller bow shape is used to maximise the volume of the ship for a given length.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] The bow may be reinforced to serve as an ice-breaker.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] The forward part of the bow is called the "stem" or "forestem".
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] Traditionally, the stem was a timber (or metal) post into which side planks (or plates) were joined.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] Some boats such as the Dutch barge "aak" or the clinker-built Viking longships have no straight stem, having instead a curved prow.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] From Middle Dutch *boech* (modern spelling *boeg*).
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] Although "bow" has the same ultimate origin as "bough" (from the Old English *bóg*, or *bóh* (shoulder, the bough of a tree), the nautical term is unrelated, being unknown in this use in English before 1600.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] The "prow" (French: *proue*, Latin: *prora*) is the foremost part of a ship's bow above the waterline.
[src:ship-motions/bow-watercraft] The terms *prow* and "bow" are often used interchangeably to describe the foremost part of a ship and its surrounding parts.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In physics, the **center of mass** of a distribution of mass in space (sometimes referred to as the **barycenter** or **balance point**) is the unique point at any given time where the weighted relative position of the distributed mass sums to zero.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] For a rigid body containing its center of mass, this is the point to which a force may be applied to cause a linear acceleration without an angular acceleration.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Calculations in mechanics are often simplified when formulated with respect to the center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] It is a hypothetical point where the entire mass of an object may be assumed to be concentrated to visualise its motion.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In other words, the center of mass is the particle equivalent of a given object for the application of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In the case of a single rigid body, the center of mass is fixed in relation to the body, and if the body has uniform density, it will be located at the centroid.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass may be located outside the physical body, as is sometimes the case for hollow or open-shaped objects, such as a horseshoe.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In the case of a distribution of separate bodies, such as the planets of the Solar System, the center of mass may not correspond to the position of any individual member of the system.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass is a useful reference point for calculations in mechanics that involve masses distributed in space, such as the linear and angular momentum of planetary bodies and rigid body dynamics.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In orbital mechanics, the equations of motion of planets are formulated as point masses located at the centers of mass (see Barycenter (astronomy) for details).
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass frame is an inertial frame in which the center of mass of a system is at rest with respect to the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The origins of the concept of the center of gravity (AKA center of weight, center of mass) are unknown, but it appears to have been a well-known philosophical concept in the ancient Greek world.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] It is discussed in the works of Hero of Alexandria and Pappus of Alexandria in detail in the 2nd and 3rd century CE, but makes its first known appearance in the 3rd century BCE in the writings of Archimedes of Syracuse, an ancient Greek mathematician, physicist, and engineer.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] He worked with simplified assumptions about gravity that amount to a uniform field, thus arriving at the mathematical properties of what we now call the center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Archimedes showed that the torque exerted on a lever by weights resting at various points along the lever is the same as what it would be if all of the weights were moved to a single point—their center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In his work *On Floating Bodies*, Archimedes demonstrated that the orientation of a floating object is the one that makes its center of mass as low as possible.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] He developed mathematical techniques for finding the centers of mass of objects of uniform density of various well-defined shapes.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Newton's second law is reformulated with respect to the center of mass in Euler's first law.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass is the unique point at the center of a distribution of mass in space that has the property that the weighted position vectors relative to this point sum to zero.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In analogy to statistics, the center of mass is the mean location of a distribution of mass in space.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] For a system of particles $P_{i}$ , $i=1,...,n$ , the center of mass is defined as $\mathbf {R} ={\sum _{i=1}^{n}m_{i}\mathbf {r} _{i} \over \sum _{i=1}^{n}m_{i}},$ where $m_{i}$ denotes the masses of the particles and $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ denotes the positions of the partices.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] If a continuous mass distribution has uniform density, which means that *ρ* is constant, then the center of mass is the same as the centroid of the volume.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] For particles in a system with periodic boundary conditions two particles can be neighbours even though they are on opposite sides of the system.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] This occurs often in molecular dynamics simulations, for example, in which clusters form at random locations and sometimes neighbouring atoms cross the periodic boundary.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] When a cluster straddles the periodic boundary, a naive calculation of the center of mass will be incorrect.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] A generalized method for calculating the center of mass for periodic systems is to treat each coordinate, *x* and *y* and/or *z*, as if it were on a circle instead of a line.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] where ${\bar {x}}_{0}$ is the naïve mass-weighted average position for all particles.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The true center of mass is then the value in the vector ${\bar {\mathbf {x} }}=[{\bar {x}}_{1},{\bar {x}}_{2},\ldots ,{\bar {x}}_{n}]$ , with the lowest sum of squared arc distances between the points.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The process can be repeated for all dimensions of the system to determine the complete center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The utility of the algorithm is that it allows the mathematics to determine where the "best" center of mass is, instead of guessing or using cluster analysis to "unfold" a cluster straddling the periodic boundaries.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] This approach computes the intrinsic center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The extrinsic circular mean is a popular way to estimate the center of mass, however this approach can be inaccurate.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] A body's center of gravity is the point around which the resultant torque due to gravity forces vanishes.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Where a gravity field can be considered to be uniform, the center of mass and the center of gravity will be the same.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In such a case, it is important to make the distinction between the center of gravity and the mass center.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Any horizontal offset between the two will result in an applied torque.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The mass center is a fixed property for a given rigid body (e.g., with no slosh or articulation), whereas the center of gravity may, in addition, depend upon its orientation in a non-uniform gravitational field.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In the latter case, the center of gravity will always be located somewhat closer to the main attractive body as compared to the mass center, and thus will change its position in the body of interest as its orientation is changed.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In the study of the dynamics of aircraft, vehicles and vessels, forces and moments need to be resolved relative to the mass center.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] That is true independent of whether gravity itself is a consideration.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Referring to the mass center as the center of gravity is something of a colloquialism, but it is in common usage and when gravity gradient effects are negligible, center of gravity and mass center are the same and are used interchangeably.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In physics the benefits of using the center of mass to model a mass distribution can be seen by considering the resultant of the gravity forces on a continuous body.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Consider a body *Q* of volume *V* with density *ρ*(**r**) at each point **r** in the volume.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] If the reference point **R** is chosen so that it is the center of mass, then $\iiint _{Q}\rho (\mathbf {r} )\left(\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {R} \right)dV=0,$ which means the resultant torque **T** = 0.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Because the resultant torque is zero the body will move as though it is a particle with its mass concentrated at the center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] By selecting the center of gravity as the reference point for a rigid body, the gravity forces will not cause the body to rotate, which means the weight of the body can be considered to be concentrated at the center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The linear and angular momentum of a collection of particles can be simplified by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Let the system of particles *Pi*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* of masses *mi* be located at the coordinates **r***i* with velocities **v***i*.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The law of conservation of momentum predicts that for any system not subjected to external forces the momentum of the system will remain constant, which means the center of mass will move with constant velocity.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] This applies for all systems with classical internal forces, including magnetic fields, electric fields, chemical reactions, and so on.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] More formally, this is true for any internal forces that cancel in accordance with Newton's third law.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The experimental determination of a body's center of mass makes use of gravity forces on the body and is based on the fact that the center of mass is the same as the center of gravity in the parallel gravity field near the earth's surface.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass of a body with an axis of symmetry and constant density must lie on this axis.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Thus, the center of mass of a circular cylinder of constant density has its center of mass on the axis of the cylinder.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In the same way, the center of mass of a spherically symmetric body of constant density is at the center of the sphere.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In general, for any symmetry of a body, its center of mass will be a fixed point of that symmetry.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] An experimental method for locating the center of mass is to suspend the object from two different points, in series, and each time to drop a plumb line from the suspension point.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The intersection of the two lines is the center of mass.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The shape of an object might already be mathematically determined, but it may be too complex to use a known formula.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In this case, one can subdivide the complex shape into simpler, more elementary shapes, whose centers of mass are easy to find.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] If the total mass and center of mass can be determined for each area, then the center of mass of the whole is the weighted average of the centers.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] This method can even work for objects with holes, which can be accounted for as negative masses.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] A direct development of the planimeter known as an integraph, or integerometer, can be used to establish the position of the centroid or center of mass of an irregular two-dimensional shape.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] This method can be applied to a shape with an irregular, smooth or complex boundary where other methods are too difficult.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] It was regularly used by ship builders to compare with the required displacement and center of buoyancy of a ship, and ensure it would not capsize.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The three-dimensional coordinates of the center of mass are determined by performing this experiment twice with the object positioned so that these forces are measured for two different horizontal planes through the object.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass will be the intersection of the two lines **L**1 and **L**2 obtained from the two experiments.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Engineers try to design a sports car so that its center of mass is lowered to make the car handle better, which is to say, maintain traction while executing relatively sharp turns.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The characteristic low profile of the U.S. military Humvee was designed in part to allow it to tilt farther than taller vehicles without rolling over, by ensuring its low center of mass stays over the space bounded by the four wheels even at angles far from the horizontal.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass is an important point on an aircraft, which significantly affects the stability of the aircraft.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] To ensure the aircraft is stable enough to be safe to fly, the center of mass must fall within specified limits.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] If the center of mass is ahead of the forward limit, the aircraft will be less maneuverable, possibly to the point of being unable to rotate for takeoff or flare for landing.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] If the center of mass is behind the aft limit, the aircraft will be more maneuverable, but also less stable, and possibly unstable enough so as to be impossible to fly.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The moment arm of the elevator will also be reduced, which makes it more difficult to recover from a stalled condition.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] For helicopters in hover, the center of mass is always directly below the rotorhead.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In forward flight, the center of mass will move forward to balance the negative pitch torque produced by applying cyclic control to propel the helicopter forward; consequently a cruising helicopter flies "nose-down" in level flight.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass plays an important role in astronomy and astrophysics, where it is commonly referred to as the *barycenter*.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The barycenter is the point between two objects where they balance each other; it is the center of mass where two or more celestial bodies orbit each other.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] When a moon orbits a planet, or a planet orbits a star, both bodies are actually orbiting a point that lies away from the center of the primary (larger) body.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] For example, the Moon does not orbit the exact center of the Earth, but a point on a line between the center of the Earth and the Moon, approximately 1,710 km (1,062 miles) below the surface of the Earth, where their respective masses balance.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] This is the point about which the Earth and Moon orbit as they travel around the Sun.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] If the masses are more similar, e.g., Pluto and Charon, the barycenter will fall outside both bodies.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Knowing the location of the center of gravity when rigging is crucial, possibly resulting in severe injury or death if assumed incorrectly.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] A center of gravity that is at or above the lift point will most likely result in a tip-over incident.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In general, the further the center of gravity below the pick point, the safer the lift.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] There are other things to consider, such as shifting loads, strength of the load and mass, distance between pick points, and number of pick points.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] Specifically, when selecting lift points, it is very important to place the center of gravity at the center and well below the lift points.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center of mass of the adult human body vertically is 10 cm above the trochanter (where the femur joins the hip), 1.4 cm forward of the knee and 1.0 cm behind the trochanter.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] In kinesiology and biomechanics, the center of mass is an important parameter that assists people in understanding their human locomotion.
[src:ship-motions/centre-of-mass] The center-of-gravity method is a method for convex optimization which uses the center of gravity of the feasible region.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The *vertical/Z axis*, or *yaw axis*, is an imaginary line running vertically through the ship and through its centre of mass.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] A yaw motion is a side-to side movement of the bow and stern of the ship.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The *transverse/Y axis*, *lateral axis*, or *pitch axis* is an imaginary line running horizontally across the ship and through the centre of mass.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] A pitch motion is an up-or-down movement of the bow and stern of the ship.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The *longitudinal/X axis*, or *roll axis*, is an imaginary line running horizontally through the length of the ship, through its centre of mass, and parallel to the *waterline*.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] A roll motion is a side-to-side or port-starboard tilting motion of the superstructure around this axis.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] There are three special axes in any ship, called longitudinal, transverse and vertical axes.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The angular movements around them—affecting the ship's moment of inertia, which sets the torque it requires to rotate in any direction—are the ship's *rotational motions* (or *rotary motions*), known as roll, pitch, and yaw respectively.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The tilting rotation of a vessel about its longitudinal/X (front-back or bow-stern) axis.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] An offset or deviation from normal on this axis is referred to as list or heel.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] Heel refers to an offset that is intentional or expected, as caused by wind pressure on sails, turning, or other crew actions.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The rolling motion towards a steady state (or list) angle due to the ship's own weight distribution is referred in marine engineering as list.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] List normally refers to an unintentional or unexpected offset, as caused by flooding, battle damage, shifting cargo, etc.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The up/down rotation of a vessel about its transverse/Y (side-to-side or port-starboard) axis.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] An offset or deviation from normal on this axis is referred to as *trim* or *out of trim*.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] A vessel that is pitching back and forth is usually termed to be hobby horsing.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The turning rotation of a vessel about its vertical/Z axis.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] An offset or deviation from normal on this axis is referred to as deviation or set.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] This is referred to as the heading of the boat relative to a magnetic compass (or true heading if referenced to the true north pole); it also affects the bearing.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] A ship can also move linearly along any of its axes—longitudinal, transverse, and vertical.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] These *translational motions* (or *translatory motions*) are known as surge, sway, and heave respectively.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The linear longitudinal (front/back or bow/stern) motion imparted by maritime conditions, usually head or following seas, or by accelerations imparted by the propulsion system.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The linear transverse (side-to-side or port-starboard) motion.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] This motion is generated directly either by the water and wind motion, particularly lateral wave motion, exerting forces against the hull or by the ship's own propulsion; or indirectly by the inertia of the ship while turning.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] This movement can be compared to the vessel's lateral drift from its course.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] The linear vertical (up/down) motion; excessive downward heave can swamp a ship.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] There are methods for both passive and active motion stabilization used in some designs.
[src:ship-motions/ship-motions] They include static hull features such as skegs and bilge keels, or active mechanical devices like counterweights, antiroll tanks and stabilizers.
